  <title>TGA/DSC-FTIR Characterization of Oxide  Nanaoparticles</title>
  <metadata>
  <md:content-id>m23038</md:content-id><md:title>TGA/DSC-FTIR Characterization of Oxide  Nanaoparticles</md:title>
  <md:abstract>In this module the application of TGA-FTIR for metal oxide nanoparticles is presented. This method is demonstrated on a sample of WO3-x nanorods synthesized via a solvothermal method.</md:abstract>
  <md:uuid>1980e53d-ee0a-46b1-b305-dfd1ad56899c</md:uuid>
</metadata>

<content>
    
    <section id="id1170644666329">
      <title>Metal oxide nanoparticles</title>
      <para id="id1170644628417">The binary compound of one or more oxygen atoms with at least one metal atom that forms a structure ≤100 nm is classified as metal oxide (MO<sub>x</sub>) nanoparticle. MO<sub>x</sub> nanoparticles have exceptional physical and chemical properties (especially if they are smaller than 10 nm) that are strongly related to their dimensions and to their morphology. These enhanced features are due to the increased surface to volume ratio which has a strong impact on the measured binding energies. Based on theoretical models, binding or cohesive energy is inversely related to particle size with a linear relationship <link target-id="id1170644298783"/>. 

</para>
      <equation id="id1170644298783"><m:math>
		<m:semantics>
			<m:mrow>
