        <para id="id1170645234509">Where <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis> is the intensity of the samples, <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis><emphasis effect="italics"><sub>b</sub></emphasis> is the intensity of the background, <emphasis effect="italics">c</emphasis> is the concentration of the compound, <emphasis effect="italics">ε</emphasis> is the molar extinction coefficient and <emphasis effect="italics">l</emphasis> is the distance that light travels through the material. A transformation of transmission to absorption spectra is usually performed and the actual concentration of the component can be calculated by applying the Beer-Lambert law <link target-id="id1170645337336"/>.</para>
        
